<section class="key-takeaways-section post-event-only" id="keyTakeaways">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="key-takeaways-header reveal">
      <span class="label label--accent">Key Takeaways</span>
      <h2 class="key-takeaways-title">What Emerged from the Dialogue</h2>
      <p class="key-takeaways-sub">
        Three central themes crystallized from 60 minutes of cross-sector civic dialogue.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="key-takeaways-grid">
      <div class="key-takeaway-card reveal">
        <div class="key-takeaway-number">01</div>
        <h3 class="key-takeaway-title">Institutional Speed Gap</h3>
        <p class="key-takeaway-text">
          The challenge isn't AI capability — it's that institutions adapt at decade-long cycles while technology moves in months. Policy, education, and workforce systems are structurally misaligned with the pace of change.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="key-takeaway-card reveal">
        <div class="key-takeaway-number">02</div>
        <h3 class="key-takeaway-title">Trust Architecture</h3>
        <p class="key-takeaway-text">
          Both regulators and builders agreed: transparency is non-negotiable. The public needs to understand not just what AI does, but how decisions about its deployment are made and who is accountable.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="key-takeaway-card reveal">
        <div class="key-takeaway-number">03</div>
        <h3 class="key-takeaway-title">Citizen Agency</h3>
        <p class="key-takeaway-text">
          AI literacy should be as foundational as reading and writing. Citizens need tools to participate in decisions that affect them — not as passive subjects of automation, but as informed stakeholders.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="key-takeaways-cta reveal">
